subsection.p:
But there is one more piece. A tiny polar box does not have area \Delta r\,\Delta\theta. It has area approximately r\,\Delta r\,\Delta\theta. So the integral should be V= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^3 (9-r^2)r\,dr\,d\theta. Compute:
V \amp= \int_0^{2\pi} \left[ \frac92r^2-\frac14r^4 \right]_0^3 d\theta \amp= \int_0^{2\pi} \left( \frac92\cdot9-\frac14\cdot81 \right) d\theta \amp= \int_0^{2\pi} \frac{81}{4}\,d\theta \amp= \frac{81\pi}{2}.
Thus \boxed{ V=\frac{81\pi}{2}. }

