statement.p:
If f is continuous on D, then
\boxed{ \iint_D f(x,y)\,dA = \int_\alpha^\beta \int_{g(\theta)}^{h(\theta)} f(r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta)\,r\,dr\,d\theta. }
Equivalently, in form language,
\boxed{ \int_D f(x,y)\,dx\wedge dy = \int_\alpha^\beta \int_{g(\theta)}^{h(\theta)} f(r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta)\,r\,dr\,d\theta. }

subsection.p:
If D=\{(x,y):0\le r\le a\}, then
\iint_D F(r)\,dA \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^a F(r)\,r\,dr\,d\theta \amp= 2\pi\int_0^a F(r)\,r\,dr.
So for radially symmetric functions on centered disks, \boxed{ \iint_D F(r)\,dA = 2\pi\int_0^a F(r)\,r\,dr. }

statement.p:
A circular pile of sand has height h(r)=12-3r over the disk 0\le r\le4. The total volume is
V \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^4 (12-3r)r\,dr\,d\theta \amp= 2\pi\int_0^4 (12r-3r^2)\,dr \amp= 2\pi\left[6r^2-r^3\right]_0^4 \amp= 2\pi(96-64) \amp= 64\pi.
Thus \boxed{ V=64\pi. }

